Using the `==` operator to compare strings in Java is not recommended and can lead to bugs in certain situations. This is because `==` checks for object identity, not content. In other words, it compares two references to determine if they point to the same object in memory, not whether their values (contents) are equal.

When comparing strings, you should use the `equals()` method instead, which compares their contents (values). The `equals()` method is defined in the `java.lang.Comparable<String>` interface that all String objects implement.

Here's a summary of when to use `==` versus `equals()`:

- Use `==` to compare primitive values (e.g., int, float, boolean) or references of objects (e.g., checking if two variables point to the same object).
- Use `equals()` to compare the content (value) of objects that implement the `equals()` method, such as strings.

In your case, you ran into a bug when comparing strings with `==` because strings are objects in Java, and `==` checks for object identity instead of content equality. Using `equals()` instead will help avoid such bugs.

Here's an example that demonstrates why `==` is not a good choice for comparing strings:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello"; // These two strings are stored at the same location in memory.
String str3 = new String("hello"); // This string is created at a different location in memory.

if (str1 == str2) { // This will evaluate to true since they point to the same object in memory.
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal using ==");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not equal using ==");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) { // This will also evaluate to true since they have the same content.
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal using equals()");
}

if (str1 == str3) { // This will evaluate to false since they point to different objects in memory.
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are equal using =="); // <-- Wrong! This will not print!
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are not equal using ==");
}

if (str1.equals(str3)) { // This will evaluate to false since they have different content (different objects).
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are equal using equals()"); // <-- Correct! This will print false.
}
```

In summary, while you can use `==` to compare primitive values and object references, you should use the `equals()` method to compare strings or any other objects that implement the `equals()` method in Java.

